f parents&quot;. &#10;one possible reason for this trend might be so parents dont expose their children to people with these sorts of snotty, superior, scathing attitudes. i would suggest a few other reasons: desire to not have the children in receipt of &quot;perceived&quot; political indocrination; school yard safety for the offspring; dislike of certain demographics; better chance of having achievers in social networks in later life. &#10;that is just my speculation, but if anyone thinks parents are paying $30k per annum per child to go to a school where the &quot;perceived&quot; benefits are imaginary, then i have a pretty good idea which party is living in (ideological) denial. &#10;no, i did not go to a private school."/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="959" language="en" documentId="4533" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="alexander" date="September 04, 2013, 10:43AM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://www.theage.com.au/comment/private-schools-and-the-art-of-ripping-off-parents-20130903-2t357.html" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="4533" notes="" title="Private schools and the art of ripping off parents"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="274"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="275" end="684"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="685" end="921"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="922" end="959"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51"/></xmi:XMI>